Raw dev notes -- March 2026

Just shipped something I'm really proud of. A client's accounting team was drowning in
manual data entry -- they receive dozens of supplier invoices per week as PDFs (via email,
Google Drive, scanned copies). For each one, someone has to open the PDF, manually read
the supplier name, invoice number, line items, amounts, VAT, and type it all into their
ERP system. Then verify the totals match. It takes 15-30 minutes per invoice and it's
mind-numbingly tedious work.

I built a system that does this automatically with AI. The cool part: it runs entirely
on Google Apps Script -- no servers, no deployment pipeline, no infrastructure to maintain.
The accounting team already lives in Google Sheets, so the whole system sits inside their
existing workflow.

How it works:
- A file watcher monitors their inbox folder for new PDFs
- Gemini AI extracts structured data: supplier info, line items, amounts, dates
- If the fast model (Flash) isn't confident, it automatically upgrades to a larger model
- Results go into a spreadsheet the team already uses
- The system generates export files in the exact format their ERP expects
- I built a Hebrew web dashboard where the team can review and approve extractions

The challenges were NOT what I expected:
- Multi-invoice PDFs: some suppliers bundle 5+ invoices into one file. Had to detect that,
  split them, extract unique invoice numbers, and merge rows for the same invoice.
- The AI hallucinated dates. Like, completely made-up dates. Had to add validation ranges
  and trigger re-extraction with the stronger model when dates look wrong.
- Hebrew RTL rendering in the web dashboard was a headache. Right-to-left text layout
  breaks in surprising ways when mixed with numbers and English text.
- Apps Script has a 6-minute execution timeout. With dozens of invoices to process,
  I had to build a checkpoint/resume system so processing continues across runs.
- The ERP import format is extremely strict: specific tab delimiters, DD/MM/YY dates,
  exact column positions. One wrong character and the import fails silently.

I'm especially proud of the model fallback logic. Flash handles ~85% of invoices
correctly. The ones it struggles with (bad handwriting, unusual layouts, multi-page)
automatically escalate. I save both model responses for comparison so I can improve
the prompts over time.

What started as 'just parse some PDFs' turned into a full accounts-payable automation.
The client went from 30 minutes per batch to a 5-minute review workflow. Classic scope
creep, but the result genuinely saves them hours every week.

This connects to something I've been thinking about a lot: AI doesn't need to be a
fancy chatbot to be valuable. Sometimes the biggest impact is just removing tedious
manual work from someone's day. The accounting team doesn't care about the AI -- they
care that they don't have to squint at PDFs anymore.
